TY  - JOUR
AU  - Acemoglu, Daron
AU  - Hassan, Tarek A.
AU  - Tahoun, Ahmed
T1  - The Power of the Street: Evidence from Egypt’s Arab Spring
PY  - 2018
Y1  - 2018/01/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhx086
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 31
IS  - 1
SP  - 1
EP  - 42
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Unprecedented street protests brought down Mubarak’s government and ushered in an era of competition between three rival political groups in Egypt. Using daily variation in the number of protesters, we document that more intense protests are associated with lower stock market valuations for firms connected to the group currently in power relative to non-connected firms, but have no impact on the relative valuations of firms connected to rival groups. These results suggest that street protests serve as a partial check on political rent-seeking. General discontent expressed on Twitter predicts protests but has no direct effect on valuations.Received February 12, 2016; editorial decision April 5, 2017 by Editor Andrew Karolyi.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhx086
ER  - 



